Ilione of Pacuvius⁷ a play to which Cicero refers more than once, and from which he quotes the same words (Tusc. Disp. 1. 44. 106, Acad. 2. 27. 88, pro Sest. 59. 1 26). Ilione, the daughter of Priam and the wife of Polymnestor, had in this ver- sion of the story substituted her brother Polydorus (see Virg. Aen. 3. 49 follJ for her son Deiphilus. Deiphilus has been killed under this error by his father, and his shade rises and calls on his mother Ilione, ‘ Mater, te appello, quae curam somno suspensam levas⁷ Neque te mei miseret, surge et repete natum.' Fufius, who is acting the part of Ilione, seems to have gone really to sleep, and not to have been waked by the appeals of Catienus who acted Dei- hilus.
